# Mapping Components

## Context
Prototypes include custom map pages for drawing a red line boundary and checking overlap with EDP (Environmental Delivery Plan) areas. Map pages are full-screen and use GeoJSON and turf for geometry.

## Map Pages in Journeys
- **Red line boundary**: User draws a polygon for the development site (e.g. `/nrf-estimate-4/map`). Optional: upload shapefile/GeoJSON instead (separate upload page).
- **EDP check**: Boundary is checked against EDP GeoJSON; if no intersection, user is sent to an exit page (e.g. `/nrf-estimate-4/no-edp`).
- **LPA / approval**: Some journeys show a read-only map with the development boundary (e.g. approve-details page).

## Layout and Assets
- **Layout**: Map pages extend `layouts/map.html` (not `main.html`) for full-screen map UX.
- **Libraries**: MapLibre GL (or Leaflet), Mapbox GL Draw (or equivalent) for drawing; turf.js for intersection/geometry.
- **Layers**: GeoJSON in `app/assets/map-layers/` (e.g. catchments, GCN EDP). Routes may load these once at startup and cache in memory.

## Route Responsibilities
- **GET map page**: Pass `data` and any config (e.g. catchments URL, initial centre). Ensure session has `mapReferrer` or similar for back link.
- **POST map page**: Receive boundary (e.g. JSON body or hidden form field). Validate polygon; run EDP intersection (e.g. turf.booleanIntersects); set `req.session.data.redlineBoundaryPolygon` and intersection result; redirect to next step or to no-edp.
- **API for EDP check**: Optional GET/POST endpoint (e.g. `/nrf-estimate-4/api/check-edp-intersection`) that accepts coordinates and returns intersection result for client-side use before submit.

## Data Stored for Boundary
- **redlineBoundaryPolygon**: Coordinates array or GeoJSON; optionally `intersectingCatchment` (or similar) from EDP intersection for display in summary and emails.
- **hasRedlineBoundaryFile**: Whether user chose “Upload a file”; if false, they used the map.

## Client-Side Behaviour (when implementing)
- **Drawing**: Draw polygon; “Save and continue” sends coordinates to server (or form submit). Button can be enabled only when a valid polygon exists (client-side validation).
- **Validation message**: If user submits without drawing: “Draw a red line boundary to continue” (match prompt).
- **Controls**: “Show all England”, “Zoom to boundary”, “Toggle catchments” (if applicable) for UX only; no need to persist in session.

## EDP Data and Performance
- Load GeoJSON once in the route module (or a shared lib) at startup; avoid reading from disk on every request.
- Use turf for intersection: `turf.booleanIntersects(boundaryPolygon, edpFeature)`; collect intersecting EDP names for redirect logic and display.

## Examples

### ✅ Good – EDP check in route (conceptual)
```javascript
const { ROUTES, TEMPLATES } = require('../config/nrf-estimate-4/routes')
const turf = require('@turf/turf')

function checkEDPIntersections(coordinates) {
  if (!coordinates || coordinates.length < 3) return { nutrient: null, intersections: [] }
  const boundaryPolygon = turf.polygon([coordinates])
  const intersections = []
  for (const feature of nutrientEdpData.features) {
    if (turf.booleanIntersects(boundaryPolygon, feature)) {
      intersections.push({ type: 'nutrient', name: feature.properties.Label || 'EDP Area' })
    }
  }
  return { nutrient: intersections[0]?.name || null, intersections }
}
```

### ✅ Good – Map page title and back link
- Page title: “Draw a red line boundary – Get a quote for Nature Restoration Fund levy – GOV.UK”.
- Back link: Previous step (e.g. redline-map or start) from `req.session.data.mapReferrer` or route constant.

### ❌ Poor – Reading GeoJSON on every request
```javascript
router.get(ROUTES.MAP, (req, res) => {
  const geojson = JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync(path.join(__dirname, '../assets/map-layers/catchments.geojson'), 'utf8'))
  res.render(TEMPLATES.MAP, { data: req.session.data, catchments: geojson })
})
```
Prefer loading at module load and reusing a cached variable.
